		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://ventureburn.com/?p=201169</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>NVision has raised a $55 million Series B financing round. The investment led by global healthcare giant Abbott signals a paradigm shift in how diseases like cancer are diagnosed, monitored,</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/nvision-raises-55m-to-expand-quantum-healthcare-tech/" data-wpel-link="internal">NVision Raises $55M to Expand Quantum Healthcare Tech</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://n.vision/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">NVision </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">has raised a $55 million Series B </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/forus-raises-160m-to-advance-modern-medicine/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">financing </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">round. The investment led by global healthcare giant Abbott signals a paradigm shift in how diseases like cancer are diagnosed, monitored, and treated using the power of quantum mechanics.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The round was anchored by Abbott, marking its first strategic move into the quantum diagnostics space. Other participants included high-profile investors Playground Global, Entrée Capital, and Matterwave Ventures and a $17 million venture loan from the European Investment Bank (EIB). </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">This fresh capital brings NVision’s total funding to $120 million, positioning the Ulm-based firm as a dominant player in the emerging quantum health sector.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Beyond Imaging: A New Era of Metabolic Insights</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">For decades, MRI technology has relied on capturing the physical structure (morphology) of tumours, measuring if they grow or shrink over months. NVision’s flagship platform, POLARIS, flips this script. By utilising quantum-enhanced sensing, the platform boosts the magnetic resonance signal of metabolic agents (such as sugar molecules) by over 10,000 times.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">This hyperpolarisation allows clinicians to see the metabolism of a disease in real-time. </span>Instead of waiting months to see if a tumour has physically shrunk, doctors can now observe whether a treatment is effectively starving a cancer cell. This can be done within hours or days of the first dose.</p>
<div id="attachment_201170" style="width: 1034px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-201170" class="size-large wp-image-201170" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/nvision-1536x864-1-1024x576.png" alt="nvision logo" width="1024" height="576" /><p id="caption-attachment-201170" class="wp-caption-text">Source: nvision</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">&#8220;We are moving from a world where we look at shadows to a world where we see the biological engine of the disease,&#8221; said Sella Brosh, CEO and co-founder of NVision. &#8220;This funding allows us to bridge the gap between drug design and real-world validation.&#8221;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/forus-raises-160m-to-advance-modern-medicine/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">Forus Raises $160M to Advance Modern Medicine</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">The Pixie Expansion: From Sensing to Computing</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Coinciding with the funding, NVision revealed a major strategic expansion: a move into quantum computing. While developing their MRI enhancement technology, the company’s scientists discovered a unique class of organic molecule-based qubits.</span></p>
<p>Unlike traditional qubits needing extreme cooling, NVision&#8217;s new qubits are integrated into Photonic Integrated Quantum Circuits (PIQC), nicknamed &#8216;Pixie&#8217;. These circuits use standard semiconductor processes, offering a more scalable and stable path than superconducting quantum computing methods.</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The ultimate goal is a closed-loop system for drug development. </span>Quantum computers will simulate and design new drug molecules for hard-to-treat diseases. The POLARIS platform will provide high-speed in vivo validation to prove drugs are working as intended.</p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Global Rollout and Institutional Adoption</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The capital injection will immediately fund the global deployment of POLARIS systems. </span>The technology is being installed at Memorial Sloan Kettering, the University of Cambridge, and TU Munich. By the end of 2026, NVision expects 20 centres across the U.S., Europe, and Asia to be using the platform.</p>
<p>The system works with existing clinical MRI machines, so hospitals need not replace their imaging suites. &#8220;Quantum isn&#8217;t just a future concept; it&#8217;s a practical tool delivering value in hospitals today,&#8221; said Peter Barrett. &#8220;By combining sensing and computation, they are defining a new category of quantum-driven healthcare.&#8221;</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/nvision-raises-55m-to-expand-quantum-healthcare-tech/" data-wpel-link="internal">NVision Raises $55M to Expand Quantum Healthcare Tech</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
