					<description><![CDATA[<p>Casimir Inc., one of the first business ventures to emerge from the media attention surrounding quantum vacuum energy, announced that it had obtained $12 million of oversubscribed seed funding. Scout</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/casimir-raises-12m-for-quantum-energy-chip-launch/" data-wpel-link="internal">Casimir Raises $12M for Quantum Energy Chip Launch</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://www.casimirspace.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">Casimir Inc.</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">, one of the first business ventures to emerge from the media attention surrounding quantum vacuum energy, announced that it had obtained $12 million of oversubscribed seed </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/vapi-raises-50m-to-expand-enterprise-voice-ai/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">funding</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">. </span>Scout Ventures led this funding round. The capital will support the launch of the MicroSparc. It is a semiconductor chip that draws energy from the quantum vacuum. This means it needs no battery, charging cable, or internal fuel.</p>
<p>Deep-tech and venture-focused investors backed the round. These included Lavrock Ventures, Cottonwood Technology, and Capital Factory. American Deep Tech and Tim Draper of Draper Associates also participated. The startup initially aimed to raise $8 million. However, strong investor interest pushed the round to $12 million.</p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Harvesting the &#8220;Empty&#8221; Space</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Founded by Dr Harold “Sonny” White, a former NASA advanced propulsion researcher known for his work on warp drive theory and vacuum physics, Casimir is built on the principle of the Casimir effect. This quantum phenomenon occurs when electromagnetic fluctuations in a vacuum create a measurable force between closely spaced conductive surfaces. While science has recognized this effect for nearly a century, converting it into usable electricity has remained an elusive &#8220;holy grail&#8221; of physics.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_201146" style="width: 490px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-201146" class="size-full wp-image-201146" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Casimir.jpg" alt="Casimir" width="480" height="159" /><p id="caption-attachment-201146" class="wp-caption-text">Source: Casimir</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Casimir’s breakthrough lies in its proprietary Casimir cavity architecture. By integrating a stationary antenna, or &#8220;micropillar&#8221;, array between conductive walls at the nanoscale, the MicroSparc chip creates a voltage potential. This allows for a continuous flow of electrons, essentially &#8220;mining&#8221; energy from the quantum vacuum field. Unlike traditional batteries, which store energy chemically and degrade over time, Casimir’s chips are designed to provide a steady output for years with zero degradation.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/vapi-raises-50m-to-expand-enterprise-voice-ai/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">Vapi Raises $50M to Expand Enterprise Voice AI</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Targeting a $10 Billion IoT Market</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The company’s first-generation product, the MicroSparc chip, measures just 5mm × 5mm. It is engineered to produce approximately 1.5 volts at 25 microamps, providing roughly 40 microwatts of continuous power. Amazingly, this output is small-scale even by a phone battery&#8217;s standards, yet perfect for this fast-growing &#8220;set-and-forget&#8221; electronics industry. Preliminary applications are the Internet of Things (IoT) and Ultra Low Power (ULP) devices, for which switching costs can outweigh the device costs. Main target markets are:</span></p>
<ul>
<li style="font-weight: 400"><b>Industrial Sensors</b><span style="font-weight: 400">: Monitoring infrastructure in inaccessible or unsafe environments.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400"><b>Medical Wearables</b><span style="font-weight: 400">: Already providing a steady stream of power to always-on health monitors like the pacemaker.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400"><b>Automotive</b><span style="font-weight: 400">: Lifetime TPMS systems (monitor the pressure of tyres).</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400"><b>Defence:</b><span style="font-weight: 400"> Low signature power for remote field sensors.</span></li>
</ul>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Roadmap to 2028 and Beyond</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The $12 million in new capital will support the efficient operation of the chip by increasing chip performance and reducing the manufacturing process while integrating via well-established existing standard semiconductor fabrication techniques. Leveraging existing silicon foundry infrastructure is a clever strategic move, as Casimir can now scale without building custom multi-billion-dollar factories.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Casimir has targeted a commercial release for 2028. Although early development centers around low-power IoT applications, the company&#8217;s long-term roadmap is arguably much more ambitious. By stacking these chips or scaling the cavity structures, the firm believes the technology could eventually power consumer electronics, electric vehicles, and even residential homes, tapping into a total addressable market estimated at over $67 billion.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The project was incubated at the Limitless Space Institute (LSI) and has received historical support through DARPA-funded research. As artificial intelligence continues to drive a massive surge in demand for persistent, edge-based computing, Casimir’s battery-free architecture offers a glimpse into a future of &#8220;autonomous energy&#8221; where devices are powered by the very fabric of space-time</span></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/casimir-raises-12m-for-quantum-energy-chip-launch/" data-wpel-link="internal">Casimir Raises $12M for Quantum Energy Chip Launch</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
